UNOFFICIAL COPY 25 RS BR 1933
1 AN ACT proposing to amend Section 172B of the Constitution of Kentucky
2 relating to property exempt from taxation.
3 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
4 Section 1. Are you in favor of expanding a freeze on the assessment or
5 reassessment of real property for property tax purposes in order to encourage the
6 development, repair, rehabilitation, or restoration of the real property for a length of time
7 determined by the General Assembly by amending the Constitution of Kentucky to read
8 as stated below?
9 Section 2. It is proposed that Section 172B of the Constitution of Kentucky be
10 amended to read as follows:
11 Notwithstanding contrary provisions of Sections 170, 171, 172, or 174 of this
12 Constitution, the General Assembly may provide by general law that the governing
13 bodies of county, municipal, and urban-county governments may declare property
14 assessment or reassessment moratoriums for qualifying units of real property for the
15 purpose of encouraging the development, repair, rehabilitation, or restoration[ of existing
16 improvements] thereon. Prior to the enactment of any property assessment or
17 reassessment moratorium program, the General Assembly shall provide or direct the local
18 governing authority to provide property qualification standards for participation in the
19 program and a limitation on the duration of any assessment or reassessment moratorium.
20 [ In no instance shall any such moratorium extend beyond five years for any particular
21 unit of real property and improvements thereon.]
22 Section 3. This amendment shall be submitted to the voters of the
23 Commonwealth for their ratification or rejection at the time and in the manner provided
24 for under Sections 256 and 257 of the Constitution, KRS 118.415, and under Sections 4
25 and 5 of this Act.
26 Section 4. Notwithstanding any provision of KRS 118.415 to the contrary, the
27 Secretary of State shall cause the question in Section 1 of this Act and the entirety of the
